Tom and Mike,<br><br>
I don't feel Kali Tal is the real issue, despite the fact that her words were her words, she wrote them, and not involuntarily I might add, and regardless of what we imagine to be her intent. There is a real credibility problem if &quot;private&quot; comments really diverge from &quot;public&quot; appearances. <br><br>
I feel the issue is that anything that invalidates or is perceived to invalidate the Vietnam Veteran is worthy of being kicked around for a while. Doc Spatz did make it a point to solicit KT's comments, and he reacted in the way he felt at the moment. Others shared some of his feelings, had their own feelings, too, and also reacted. That's normal. Like so many similar situations that I have seen here, and in life, I have personally found that after a few hefty bounces, the reactions decay down, slowly die off, and things move on to the next event.<br><br>
Self-esteem is the key. Protecting that self-esteem is the defense.<br><br>
As far as the merits of KT's site is concerned, I share some of your opinions. It is true that it probably is not worth the effort. KT is free to run her site as she chooses. I choose not to bother with it. However, my perceptions and feelings are still very real, and if I feel that the site appears one step removed from a goose-stepping control freak site with an attitude that smells as bad as a road kill skunk, that is my entitlement. If I bounce along for a while with it, that's OK too. 
